  <h1>Userpedia</h1>
  <h2>an open registry for all internet users</h2>

  <p>The social web stinks right now:  we have a handful of proprietary networks that let you respond to other people using proprietary usernames, like @jack and +SergeyBrin. Thus far, we open web folk have proposed alternative solutions that rely on email addresses. But let's get real, the domain part in @gmail.com and @job.co have always been temporary masters, just like the @yahoo.com and @past.co that came before them. Clearly, we need something different.</p>
  
  <p id="crazy-dream">
  Enter one programmer's crazy dream:<br />
  a free username registry that all the open web can use,<br />
  liberating us from proprietary network handles and dangling domains.<br />
  </p>

  <p>I call it the <em>Userpedia</em> and hope to widely distinguish its usernames by prepending them with asterisks (just like pointers in C). That's right my code-loving friends, we're making a dereference operator for people. Lay folk should feel free to call them starnames.</p>

