  <h2>Extended Q&A</h2>
  <p class="center">(collected from questions you've asked)</p>

  <p>Q: Is the Userpedia a strictly real name system where I can only have one username?</p>
  <p>A: The Userpedia is not necessarily a real name system, but the rules do state clearly that "you" can only have one username. If, however, for the sake of privacy, a person requires multiple identities (and therefore "you"s) to exist, then the Userpedia wholeheartedly encourages that each identity be allocated a username. All that said, squatters and spam bots are never allowed and, upon discovery, will be quickly and judiciously dealloced.</p>

  <p>Q: Why is there a Facebook login after I register or try to register?</p>
  <p>A: We've made the Userpedia an invite-only registry in order to minimize on spammers and squatters. While we let you individually invite people you know by email, we also want a quick way for you to grant the people you know access to the Userpedia. This in mind, if you login with Facebook, your Facebook friends will be able to register by logging in with Facebook on the Userpedia. By the way, we only store Facebook User IDs on our server and will never make them public. Finally, at some point, we will disable Facebook login and destroy the collected Facebook User IDs.</p>

  <p>Q: Is this going to be federated?</p>
  <p>A: While the registry itself is singular, Userpedia is intended to allow for the creation of user-level federation. In this way, the Userpedia is analogous to DNS, which though also singular, serves as the basis for domain-level federation.</p>

  <p>Q: What kinds of user-level protocols could be built on top of the Userpedia?</p>
  <p>A: *foy is going to make a user-to-user better-than-email protocol. Other potential protocols for others to build may include a user-to-user file transfer protocol, a user federated social broadcast protocol, or a social search protocol.</p>

  <p>Q: Why another username?</p>
  <p>A: This is it, the last one, we swear. More seriously, all the major identity vendors are tied to proprietary services. The Userpedia differs from them, in being no more than a username registry that will let others build out all the interesting apps, services, and protocols.</p>

  <p>Q: Have you heard of i-names?<p>
  <p>A: Yes, i-names were unfortunately tied to a fairly complicated XDI thing (we're not sure what to call it) and entailed annual registration fees through i-brokers. In contrast, the Userpedia is intended to be simple and free.</p>

  <p>Q: Why don't you charge for this?</p>
  <p>A: The Userpedia, like the Wikipedia, is intended to be for everyone, including those without discretionary income to spend. Moreover, because the Userpedia will offer such a simple service, we estimate that operating costs should be manageable low. If the Userpedia does become overwhelmingly popular and operating costs do become a problem, we may seek out donations or enlist the assistance of other organizations to act as regional mirrors.</p>

